al theory, literature, and philosophy-use Malabou's innovative combination of post-structuralism and neuroscience to evaluate the political implications of her work. They address, among other things, subjectivity, science, war, the malleability of sexuality, neoliberalism and economic theory, indigenous and racial politics, and the relationship between the human and non-human. Plastic Materialities also includes three essays by Malabou and an interview with her, all of which bring her work into conversation with issues of sovereignty, justice, and social order for the first time.Contributors. Brenna Bhandar, Silvana Carotenuto, Jonathan Goldberg-Hiller, Jairus Victor Grove, Catherine Kellogg, Catherine Malabou, Renisa Mawani, Fred Moten, Alain Pottage, Michael J. Shapiro, Alberto Toscano  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAdaptability (Psychology) 0aAdaptability (Psychology). 0aBrainxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy of mind. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aPottage, Alain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToscano, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhandar, Brenna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBhandar, Brenna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKellogg, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalabou, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoten, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg-Hiller, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrove, Jairus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg-Hiller, Jonatha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg-Hiller, Jon